# csvprof — Streaming CSV Data Profiler
 
A command-line data profiling tool written in idiomatic Rust. Ingests any CSV file
and produces a structured report describing the shape, quality, and statistical
characteristics of each column — **without loading the whole file into memory**.
 
## Build
 
```bash
cargo build --release
# Binary will be at: ./target/release/csvprof
```
 
## Usage
 
```bash
csvprof [OPTIONS] <FILE>
 
Arguments:
  <FILE>   Path to input CSV file. Use `-` for stdin.
 
Options:
  -p, --percentiles           Show p5 / p25 / p75 / p95 for numeric columns
  -H, --histogram             Show full frequency histogram for categoricals
  -j, --json                  Output as JSON instead of terminal tables
  -d, --delimiter <CHAR>      Field delimiter (default: comma)
      --categorical-threshold Unique-value cap for Categorical type (default: 50)
      --max-categories        Max distinct values tracked (default: 10000)
  -h, --help                  Print help
  -V, --version               Print version
```
 
## Examples
 
```bash
# Basic profile
csvprof data.csv
 
# Full stats with percentiles and histograms
csvprof data.csv -p -H
 
# JSON output (pipe to jq, etc.)
csvprof data.csv --json | jq '.columns[] | select(.inferred_type == "integer")'
 
# TSV file
csvprof data.tsv -d $'\t'
 
# Stdin
cat data.csv | csvprof -
```